text: hi everyone Anthony Fantino here
intranets busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new Lee Bannon
album alternate endings Lee Bannon is a
super versatile music producer known
mostly for his hip hop production
letting his beats the likes of pro era
as well as super helpful but the guy's
been dropping lesser-known solo albums
and EPS for years now LPS like big toy
box and fantastic plastic and Caligula
theme music and a lot of these releases
dabbling in instrumental hip hop and
some cloud rap and trap rap as well and
even though his releases have been
getting darker and more atmospheric and
chilled out and moody I didn't really
foresee the move that he was gonna make
with this record or really just the the
surprise transition he made away from
hip hop I wouldn't really say you did a
180 with his music he really did three
backflips a spin kick and a front aerial
off a two-story building landing
somewhere in Jungle break beat drum and
bass territory genres of electronic
music I remember being wildly popular
when I was a lot younger and I liked a
lot of the bigger names coming out of
them as well like the prodigy and The
Chemical Brothers and Crystal Method had
some songs I liked and then later I
drove into artists who were much more
aggressive and experimental with some of
these breakbeat drum and bass drill and
bass sounds Square pusher effects twin
and because there was a time when these
genres had crested in the in the popular
consciousness it's hard not to see the
direction that Lee Bannon takes on this
record as nostalgic and alternate
endings makes me wonder whether or not
this genre could sort of see a second
coming get popular once again especially
given that Lee Bannon has recreated
these styles with such a deep attention
to detail the LP kicks off with the
fantastic track resurrect a very speedy
break beats on this thing glitchy vocal
samples that are relentless locked into
the beaten constantly jumping up and
down in pitch sometimes chipmunks
sometimes grimy beasts lines on this
track great groove this song to me has
everything a great song in this style
should
have but bannon's sort of distinguishes
himself in this genre with an emphasis
on atmosphere executing some of these
songs with a massive amount of reverb
that might remind you of a burial record
and I know there are atmospheric drum
and bass producers like Goldie who
definitely have influenced bannon's
music but he does take the reverb he
does take the ethereal tones to an
extreme degree sometimes especially on
tracks like this opener where seems like
Lee is trying to either find or create
as much common ground as possible
between incredibly aggressive jungle and
breakbeat music and ambient interludes
these sounds also come together really
well on my favorite track here NW / WB
which has all these vocal samples from
the RZA peppered throughout the vocals
are just screaming their
attention-grabbing really reminds me of
the prodigy then there's this incredibly
infectious synth line and this lead is
so strange it's warped it's twisted the
song delivers a blazing opener but
slowly grows more panoramic and ethereal
as it continues on incorporating these
sounds in the background that sound like
haunted winds along with a lot of other
indescribable noises and glitches and
tones and little percussive flares that
are spread throughout the track again
there's a really great balance of hard
in-your-face sounds and more ethereal
sounds as well on these first two tracks
but this atmosphere sometimes can be
bannon's undoing tracks like prime /
decent and shoot out the Stars and wind
and then songs like this really set the
stage but they fail to cast a leading
role the LP really is break be wallpaper
for a little while unfortunately and
this doesn't really change until the
track Phoebe Katz where while this song
is atmospherically addicted as well the
vocal samples and the overall melodies
hanging in the atmosphere in the
background are so pretty there so
beautiful they're so serene and then
there is tu-16 another favorite of mine
on here which starts off with a very
very eerie and murky piano part right at
the beginning there are these wailing
vocal samples popping up repeatedly
throughout the track
I love the cascading keyboard phrases
over the bridge tracks like this on this
record are fantastic ones that have a
ton of detail multiple phases you really
feel like you're traveling through
different parts of the song from A to B
even though there are tracks here that I

I do think liebe Anand does bring a

Mel is kind of a detour for me not
really a highlight but still stands out
as being very psychedelic and the
closing track on here is similarly
trippy as well and then there's value 10
as well which has one of the more
standout vocal samples I love the funky

changes of pace and sound are just
enough for me
but even if you are into this sound I do
think to an extent Bannen does test
patience especially with the length of
this record and behemoths on here like

available one of my least favorite songs
on here not because of its length but
because of its really tedious lead
melody that you don't get any relief
from until about the six-minute mark of

and starts ascending up a somewhat epic
chord progression overall alternate
endings is a decent album considering
it's Lee bandhans first big commercial
release after being recently signed in
into tune records it's got some
undeniably fantastic tracks but does it
stay entertaining for the entire hour
not for me Plus at this point with
pursuing this style of music I think Lee
Bannon is doing more emulating than he
is carving a niche out for himself while
it's good and encouraging to hear that
Lee Bandhan can recreate this musical
